text: Well it's definitely taking it more serious than they did with "The Mummy"! As a huge fan of the original Universal Monsters films, this looks interesting - but it seems like an entirely separate concept. From this trailer I can't see any references to the 1933 film, or the source novel for that matter - apart from the character being invisible/insane. I must admit, I miss the gothic horror side to the originals, like what they did with "The Wolf Man" remake in 2010. A company like A24 who have made "The Lighthouse" would probably have given us something more close to the source of these films. My hopes aren't set too high, but it's definitely an improvement from the first attempt at the 'Dark Universe' concept.

text: I‚Äôm sorry, but this movie looks bad. When I heard about this, I REALLY wanted to like it. I really did. But this movie doesn‚Äôt feel like a remake of the original. The original was about a doctor who found a potion that turns him invisible. Seems cool and even wacky. A FAR cry from this. This seems to be about an abusive boyfriend (which is starting to become horror cliche) who is revived and turned invisible. This seems like the plot for one of those dumbass horror text message stories. Also, this trailer showed more than it needed to. I practically watched the whole movie just now. Here‚Äôs the plot. An abusive boyfriend dies and leaves the girlfriend relieved. However, he comes back and is invisible. She tries to tell everyone and people start thinking she‚Äôs going insane. She then finds out his secret, kills him for good, and gets her revenge. There you go. Don‚Äôt need to watch the movie now. Also the acting. I hated 1:26. That seems like the acting skills a high school freshman has when they didn‚Äôt do their homework. And then there‚Äôs 1:23. This is practically all Blumhouse movies in a nutshell. The actors being unnecessarily creepy when nothing scary is going on. It‚Äôs like they‚Äôre implying that what they‚Äôre saying isn‚Äôt creepy. Which at first IS creepy. But the more they imply that they‚Äôre not being creepy leads you to believe that what they‚Äôre saying isn‚Äôt creepy. Also, this just seems like another ‚Äúall men bad‚Äù kind of story. You can tell because it went from ‚Äúwacky doctor turns invisible‚Äù to ‚Äúabusive boyfriend dies and then haunts his girlfriend‚Äù. All I‚Äôm saying is that I don‚Äôt think this movie is going to be good. Like all other Blumhouse movies before it, it‚Äôs trying too hard to be scary. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm especially worried about what they‚Äôre going to do with FNaF and Fantasy Island.

text: Meh. This looks the sort of 40-minute story you'd see in a procedural show on TV like Fringe or The Flash. Doesn't feel like something that could fill a 2-hour movie. Plus, it feels exactly like the sort of thing we've already seen and they've already given us all the major plot beats:  - Unstable man wants revenge on woman. - Man fakes death and gives her an inheritance. - The inheritance is conditioned on her being declared mentally stable. - Man turns invisible and uses his power to make her think she's insane. - Everyone believes she's crazy because she's an idiot that doesn't carry around a spray paint can to use on the guy when she suspects he's there. - Invisible man makes a mistake and gives himself away or she finally gets clever and proves he's real. - Now everyone's on the run from an invisible man, something that's really not that much of a threat in today's world once you know he's real (again, spray paint cans or just a flour bag should do the trick). - I'm gonna go out on a limb and declare that the good guys win. Bonus points if there's a stinger that suggests the invisible guy is still around after everyone thought he died.   This is a goddamn Scooby Doo episode.

text: I saw the trailer for this when I went to see 1917, and I honestly thought it was a comedy at first. Even though the plot is about a manipulative abuser, my mind instantly sidetracked into how impractical invisibility would be. Like, imagine all the seemingly mundane things that we do daily, that would be difficult to impossible for someone who was invisible. Like, how would he travel? Or see a doctor if he was ill? Or even use the bathroom? Could you imagine walking into a public restroom, only to find a shit being taken by someone you couldn‚Äôt see? Additionally you‚Äôd basically be alone, as no one can see you and the only person who acknowledges your existence is your ex who everything thinks is crazy. It‚Äôd basically be worse than death.

text: I just watched the film and to be honest it was kind of trash and cliche. There was way too many plot holes, lack of character development, unnecessarily long scenes and literally no information about each character.  My number one disappointment was how they kept describing Adrian as a narcissist sociopath who doesn't give a shit about her but then proceeds to use this 'special' suit to stalk and haunt her. Cellia/Kass or whatever her name was also kept saying that he would beat her and abuse her however there was NO FLASHBACKS NO SCENES OF ADRIAN DOING THESE THINGS. We only the couples relationship through Kass's perspective however I'm starting to think that she was the crazy and insane one who kept creating lies?  Second thing was when Kass promised to give Sydney $10k every month for the next year James was just cool with it, like dude we need to see a realistic conversation and reaction. Anyway there's way too many things to criticise but in my opinion it was just a waste of time , WASTE OF 2 HOURS !
